Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `ProcessLoop` while loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow + cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution after abort | Remove â€” just `continue` the loop |
| `Stop()` â†’ `Thread.Abort()` | Force termination | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work â€” same logic that was
                // in the ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed â€” just let the loop
                // re-evaluate the while condition and exit
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem` must accept and honor the token.** If it blocks on a queue or I/O without checking the token, cancellation stalls. Example fix:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) â€” blocks indefinitely
var item = _queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8) â€” wakes on cancellation
var item = _queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` in the old `Stop()` was a fire-and-forget wait.** `Thread.Join(timeout)` is strictly better â€” it returns as soon as the thread exits *or* the timeout elapses.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort` had no equivalent and needs none.** The old code called `ResetAbort` to prevent the exception from re-throwing so `finally` would run cleanly. With cooperative cancellation, `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception â€” once caught, it's done.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` from unrelated tokens.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch cancellations *you* triggered, not ones from an unrelated source.

**5. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` and leaks timer handles if not disposed. The class now implements `IDisposable` to handle this.

**6. No force-kill exists in modern .NET.** If `GetNextItem` calls uncooperative third-party code that ignores the token, the thread will hang. The only fallback is to move that work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill`.
